5
00:02:29,949 --> 00:02:32,553
'You've been listening
to a programme of lunchtime music

6
00:02:32,662 --> 00:02:35,539
'by Les Norman
and his Bethnal Green Bambinos.'

7
00:03:01,716 --> 00:03:03,961
- You gonna be at that meeting tonight?
- Afraid so.

8
00:03:04,070 --> 00:03:06,390
- Try and keep it short, Dad.
- Hm.

9
00:03:07,741 --> 00:03:13,255
<i>I</i> I don't want to set the world on fire

10
00:03:13,368 --> 00:03:16,049
<i>J</i> I just want to start...

11
00:03:16,162 --> 00:03:18,886
- Pair of kippers to wait for Mrs White.
- Okey-doke.

12
00:03:18,995 --> 00:03:21,076
See any difference?

13
00:03:21,190 --> 00:03:23,707
- What's the matter? Gone off?
- No, in me.

14
00:03:23,824 --> 00:03:27,496
- What's all that oily muck?
- The shiny look, they call it.

15
00:03:27,615 --> 00:03:29,816
- Do you like it?
- Not much.

16
00:03:29,930 --> 00:03:31,935
- No wonder we're short of fat.
-  Frank!

17
00:03:34,160 --> 00:03:37,157
Frank, Mum wants to know
if you've got any cod fillets.

18
00:03:37,273 --> 00:03:39,638
I've got something better. Fancy a
nice bit of bream for your supper?

19
00:03:39,747 --> 00:03:42,940
- Mm, yes.
- Ah, it's a treat to see it again.

20
00:03:43,059 --> 00:03:46,699
My old dad used to say that this one
was the most human fish of 'em all.

21
00:03:46,811 --> 00:03:48,576
If I was a bream, I'd resent that.

22
00:03:48,686 --> 00:03:50,887
Oh, I'll tell you a most
remarkable thing about the bream.

23
00:03:51,001 --> 00:03:54,673
When he's courting,
he grows a little white wart just here.

24
00:03:54,832 --> 00:03:57,153
Just like you, or I might buy a new hat.

25
00:03:57,267 --> 00:03:59,632
Well, I must be going now.
I'm ten minutes late already.

26
00:03:59,741 --> 00:04:01,626
I'll fetch it over
with a nice big piece of ice.

27
00:04:01,736 --> 00:04:03,174
All right.

28
00:04:04,011 --> 00:04:06,572
Some people get jam on it-.

29
00:04:06,685 --> 00:04:09,049
Wrap this up and put it in the fridge.

30
00:04:17,060 --> 00:04:19,305
- Hello, Benny.
- Hello.

31
00:04:27,756 --> 00:04:30,829
Phew! 94 degrees on Air Ministry roof.

32
00:04:30,948 --> 00:04:32,551
Right, I'll keep off it.

33
00:04:32,665 --> 00:04:35,542
- Any more about us there?
- Yeah.

34
00:04:35,658 --> 00:04:40,496
"It is now believed that Pamela, the
last unexploded bomb in the London area,

35
00:04:40,606 --> 00:04:44,726
"will be removed from Miramont Place,
Pimlico, on Tuesday next."

36
00:04:44,836 --> 00:04:46,753
- We hope.
- Oh, it's gotta be, mate.

37
00:04:46,871 --> 00:04:49,595
They want it for the exhibition
on local arts and culture.

38
00:04:49,705 --> 00:04:52,550
You can pack it up, boys.

39
00:04:52,658 --> 00:04:55,775
Art and culture's had it.
We're not defusing after all.

40
00:04:55,891 --> 00:04:57,536
- Not, sir?
- We've got to blow her up.

41
00:04:57,646 --> 00:05:00,491
- What, in her state of health?
- We've got to.

42
00:05:00,600 --> 00:05:05,036
They've discovered another last bomb
so Pamela goes up tomorrow.

43
00:05:05,150 --> 00:05:08,866
The police are sending a chap
round now to warn the population.

44
00:05:10,178 --> 00:05:12,543
What are you talking about?

45
00:05:12,652 --> 00:05:15,932
Two bob to win on Silver Street
at 13 to 8. That's 5 and 3.

46
00:05:16,044 --> 00:05:18,170
Any to Come Equator, you had.

47
00:05:18,279 --> 00:05:20,763
Heard about the bomb, Fred?
Setting her off tomorrow.

48
00:05:20,873 --> 00:05:23,750
- Oh, they're setting her off, are they?
- Have to change your pitch.

49
00:05:23,866 --> 00:05:26,230
Bit of bad, Gold Cup Day.

50
00:05:30,411 --> 00:05:32,808
This one's me, all right.

51
00:05:32,925 --> 00:05:37,197
Think it'll go with my taffeta?
That check skirt I got up west?

52
00:05:37,315 --> 00:05:39,592
Lovely. Three guineas, dear.

53
00:05:39,709 --> 00:05:42,390
- Oh.
- Make it pounds. I'm easy.

54
00:05:42,503 --> 00:05:44,748
Ta, Edie.
I've got three coupons somewhere.

55
00:05:44,857 --> 00:05:48,290
- Four, dear. Same as Bond Street.
- Oh, go on, be a pal.

56
00:05:48,409 --> 00:05:50,414
I want it for Miss Pimlico night
at the Palais.

57
00:05:50,524 --> 00:05:53,641
Oh, that. Proper old fiddle. Always was.

58
00:05:53,757 --> 00:05:55,915
OK, I'll put it by.

59
00:05:56,032 --> 00:05:57,634
Oh, no.

60
00:05:57,747 --> 00:05:59,828
Look, I tell you what.

61
00:06:00,821 --> 00:06:03,066
Oh, all right.

62
00:06:03,175 --> 00:06:07,250
- Well, and what have I been up to?
- Huh! Make me blush to guess.

63
00:06:07,365 --> 00:06:11,278
Well, it's no good you settling down
for a mike. It's time I had a wet.

64
00:06:11,395 --> 00:06:14,116
I've come here to save your life.
They're blowing up that bomb tomorrow.

65
00:06:14,189 --> 00:06:16,870
- They're blowing it up?
- You'll have to take a walk.

66
00:06:16,983 --> 00:06:19,141
I suppose they couldn't make it
early closing day.

67
00:06:19,258 --> 00:06:22,778
- Wouldn't upset trade enough.
- You can't pick and choose with bombs.

68
00:06:28,716 --> 00:06:32,312
- Governor in, Bert?
- If it's about the bomb, he knows.

69
00:06:33,146 --> 00:06:37,221
- Bert! You going to be all night?
- Coming, Governor.

70
00:06:45,916 --> 00:06:51,190
A trifling matter like that, sir, I...
I didn't want to bother Head Office.

71
00:06:51,303 --> 00:06:52,502
Trifling?

72
00:06:52,620 --> 00:06:54,266
We regard it as a serious matter

73
00:06:54,376 --> 00:06:57,492
that a man in your position should make
these decisions without our authority.

74
00:06:59,604 --> 00:07:01,610
Excuse me, sir.

75
00:07:17,523 --> 00:07:19,724
Sorry, sir.

76
00:07:19,838 --> 00:07:22,115
A sense of responsibility
is a very excellent thing, Wix.

77
00:07:22,232 --> 00:07:24,149
We quite appreciate that.

78
00:07:24,945 --> 00:07:29,261
But if we start giving a free hand
to the manager of a minor branch,

79
00:07:29,375 --> 00:07:31,576
we'd find ourselves in Queer Street.

80
00:07:31,690 --> 00:07:35,526
Head Office don't consider you a second
Montagu Norman yet, you know,

81
00:07:35,641 --> 00:07:38,158
and they like to have some idea
of what's happening here.

82
00:07:38,275 --> 00:07:39,501
Then Head Office had better know

83
00:07:39,552 --> 00:07:43,627
that I and my staff intend knocking off
at three o'clock tomorrow afternoon.

84
00:07:44,460 --> 00:07:48,013
Seems funny, Arthur, having
to come and tell you about a bomb.

85
00:07:48,131 --> 00:07:51,292
You're telling me. Took a warden
to nose 'em out in the old days.

86
00:07:51,404 --> 00:07:52,962
They aren't half making
a mess-up of this one.

87
00:07:53,080 --> 00:07:55,281
He really misses
that old white helmet of his.

88
00:08:00,902 --> 00:08:02,580
Good evening, ladies.
Now, what can I do for you?

89
00:08:02,698 --> 00:08:04,060
Mum wants a mop.

90
00:08:04,174 --> 00:08:06,332
What, another? She had one last week.

91
00:08:06,449 --> 00:08:09,610
What did she do with that, eh?
Fetch your dad one over the ear with it?

92
00:08:09,722 --> 00:08:12,642
Don't tease the child, Arthur.
Give her a mop.

93
00:08:16,546 --> 00:08:19,030
- Hello! That's a new one, isn't it?
- Yes, he finished it last night.

94
00:08:19,139 --> 00:08:21,984
Spent half the morning
getting the mess off the carpet.

95
00:08:22,093 --> 00:08:25,765
It's an idea for that dump out there.
Give those kids somewhere decent to play.

96
00:08:29,875 --> 00:08:31,673
They seem to be
doing pretty well <i>as</i> it is.

97
00:08:31,791 --> 00:08:34,711
I'd have something to say
if I was their mother.

98
00:08:34,823 --> 00:08:37,008
- Nice job you've got there.
- Something to pass the time.

99
00:08:37,059 --> 00:08:38,497
Pass the time indeed!

100
00:08:38,615 --> 00:08:41,928
Stayed up till two o'clock
to get it ready for the Council meeting.

101
00:08:43,084 --> 00:08:47,084
It'll be quite simple to turn
the old water tank into a swimming pool.

102
00:08:47,195 --> 00:08:51,195
I, er... l think we've discussed
this matter long enough, gentlemen.

103
00:08:51,306 --> 00:08:55,065
Those in favour
of Mr Pemberton's, er... project.

104
00:09:00,723 --> 00:09:04,036
Those in favour of selling
this piece of ground.

105
00:09:07,827 --> 00:09:10,192
Well, that seems to settle it.

106
00:09:10,301 --> 00:09:13,418
We've got to face economic facts,
Mr Pemberton.

107
00:09:13,534 --> 00:09:16,531
This borough is in no position just now
to finance daydreams.

108
00:09:16,647 --> 00:09:18,804
That's just plain ridiculous.

109
00:09:18,921 --> 00:09:21,242
Don't you ever think of anything
besides pounds, shillings and pence?

110
00:09:21,356 --> 00:09:24,080
Withdraw that remark!

111
00:09:25,307 --> 00:09:27,791
If everybody is quite settled now,

112
00:09:27,901 --> 00:09:30,298
I should like to read
the proposed advertisement.

113
00:09:30,415 --> 00:09:36,092
"For sale, freehold. Valuable building
land in much sought-after position.

114
00:09:36,202 --> 00:09:39,558
"Eminently suitable for business
premises or factory site.

115
00:09:39,674 --> 00:09:42,954
"Heart of busy trading centre.
Unlimited prospects.

116
00:09:43,065 --> 00:09:44,983
"Full transport facilities to hand.

117
00:09:45,100 --> 00:09:48,097
"Special appeal to purchaser of vision.

118
00:09:48,213 --> 00:09:50,534
"No obstruction to future development.

119
00:09:50,648 --> 00:09:52,729
"Thoroughly safe investment."

120
00:10:07,808 --> 00:10:10,758
What have you been up to, you little devil?
Little devil, that's what you are.

121
00:10:10,761 --> 00:10:11,840
Wasn't me. It was him.

122
00:10:11,958 --> 00:10:14,879
I reckon it was about six to four
on him coming home in a sack.

123
00:10:19,022 --> 00:10:22,215
- Came down on my funny bone.
- Went right up in the air, I did.

124
00:10:22,334 --> 00:10:24,415
So will your father
when he hears about this.

125
00:10:29,917 --> 00:10:31,955
All I can say is
some people are born lucky.

126
00:10:32,072 --> 00:10:33,794
- Oh!
- Arthur!

127
00:10:34,706 --> 00:10:37,866
- Dad, where are you?
- Where is he gone?

128
00:10:39,016 --> 00:10:41,653
- Somebody do something!
- Hold on!

129
00:10:41,769 --> 00:10:43,687
- Here's a rope!
- Mr Pemberton!

130
00:10:43,805 --> 00:10:45,483
Mr Pemberton! Are you all right?

131
00:10:45,600 --> 00:10:47,562
Are you all right, Mr Pemberton?

132
00:10:47,676 --> 00:10:49,877
Oh, I'm having a grand time.

133
00:10:55,657 --> 00:10:57,738
Arthur!

134
00:10:59,129 --> 00:11:00,687
Don't worry, we're getting him up.

135
00:11:01,962 --> 00:11:03,161
Right!

136
00:11:03,279 --> 00:11:05,164
Heave!

137
00:11:05,275 --> 00:11:06,921
Take it easy!

138
00:11:07,031 --> 00:11:08,992
Stick to it, Dad! You'll make it!

139
00:11:09,106 --> 00:11:11,232
Hold tight, dear.

140
00:11:11,341 --> 00:11:13,183
You all right?

141
00:11:13,297 --> 00:11:15,901
- Hey, what happened?
- Thank you, boys.

142
00:11:16,010 --> 00:11:18,734
I'm all right. Don't worry, don't fuss.
I'm all right, I tell you.

143
00:11:18,843 --> 00:11:21,044
- You have hurt yourself.
- No, I haven't.

144
00:11:21,158 --> 00:11:23,643
- Just like old times, eh?
- Hello, Ted. Yeah, just like.

145
00:11:23,752 --> 00:11:27,272
You turn up when it's all over.

146
00:11:27,384 --> 00:11:30,020
Now, come on. Which of you was it?

147
00:11:31,016 --> 00:11:33,860
Come on. Who was it?

148
00:11:33,968 --> 00:11:36,846
- Which of you was it?
- Don't lie!

149
00:11:36,961 --> 00:11:40,438
- It's always that kid of yours.
- He never touched that wheel.

150
00:11:41,431 --> 00:11:43,197
- Steady, steady.
- Well, sit still, then.

151
00:11:43,307 --> 00:11:44,909
" - Shirley!

152
00:11:45,023 --> 00:11:47,584
OK, I'll go.

153
00:11:47,696 --> 00:11:50,181
- That'll do, that'll do.
- No, it won't. Stay where you are.

154
00:11:50,291 --> 00:11:51,936
Playing about like a schoolboy.

155
00:11:52,047 --> 00:11:53,964
I don't know why you ever wanted
to go down the blessed hole.

156
00:11:54,082 --> 00:11:56,599
I didn't want to go down the hole.
I fell down.

157
00:11:56,716 --> 00:11:59,080
Well, you shouldn't have gone so close.

158
00:11:59,190 --> 00:12:01,751
- Who was it?
- Frank with the ice.

159
00:12:02,901 --> 00:12:05,746
- You didn't go to the door like that?
- Yes, of course.

160
00:12:05,855 --> 00:12:08,579
It's the only sensible kind of thing
to wear in this kind of weather.

161
00:12:08,688 --> 00:12:12,763
Downright indecent, I call it.
Whatever must that man have thought?

162
00:12:12,878 --> 00:12:15,602
Exactly the same <i>as</i> all the other men
thought last year at Bournemouth.

163
00:12:15,711 --> 00:12:18,348
- I thought I was seeing things again.
- Seeing things?

164
00:12:18,465 --> 00:12:23,097
Yes, when all that stuff fell on my
head, I fancied I saw a kind of cave

165
00:12:23,215 --> 00:12:24,980
with a load of treasure in it.

166
00:12:25,090 --> 00:12:29,449
- Treasure?
- Yes, goblets, jewels, gold coins and...

167
00:12:29,560 --> 00:12:32,284
Look out, look out.
It's all getting down my neck.

168
00:12:37,102 --> 00:12:39,108
Did you say gold coins?

169
00:12:40,973 --> 00:12:43,577
Oh, that's one of those kids
worked off a dud on you.

170
00:12:43,687 --> 00:12:45,768
It is gold, isn't it?

171
00:12:46,800 --> 00:12:50,800
Come on. I'll fetch a ladder.
You grab a couple of torches.

172
00:12:50,910 --> 00:12:55,182
Arthur, don't be daft. Come back. Shirley!
Arthur, your supper's just on ready!

173
00:12:59,171 --> 00:13:01,209
Now, I wonder where that was.

174
00:13:11,942 --> 00:13:13,544
Oi.

175
00:13:13,657 --> 00:13:15,738
All right, all right. Come on, come on.

176
00:13:18,566 --> 00:13:20,691
Shine the light here, will you?

177
00:13:24,353 --> 00:13:26,314
Keep your light there.

178
00:13:33,771 --> 00:13:35,612
There.

179
00:13:44,426 --> 00:13:47,150
Cor! Someone's been
saving up for a rainy day.

180
00:13:47,260 --> 00:13:49,298
Look at all this stuff.

181
00:13:51,250 --> 00:13:54,095
- Look, there's a coat of arms.
- Look at this.

182
00:13:54,204 --> 00:13:56,928
Must be hundreds of years old.

183
00:14:06,256 --> 00:14:07,814
What's that?

184
00:14:07,932 --> 00:14:11,364
Hm. They even had to fill up forms
in those days.

185
00:14:11,483 --> 00:14:13,445
- Hell t
- Yes? o here!

186
00:14:13,559 --> 00:14:15,836
What on earth are you playing at?

187
00:14:16,791 --> 00:14:18,829
We've found some buried treasure
down here.

188
00:14:18,946 --> 00:14:20,864
- What?
- Loads of it, worth a million!

189
00:14:20,981 --> 00:14:22,823
Nip round to the police
and give them the wire!

190
00:14:22,937 --> 00:14:26,490
We're going to find out all about
an old picture! Meet you in the library!

191
00:14:27,726 --> 00:14:29,732
Yes, it's his
crest, right enough.

192
00:14:29,841 --> 00:14:35,159
Yes, a shield of pretense
or a lion rampant gules.

193
00:14:35,269 --> 00:14:36,434
Yes, just as I said.

194
00:14:37,304 --> 00:14:40,301
Except that you called it a mangy
old poodle up on its hind legs.

195
00:14:40,417 --> 00:14:43,054
- Well, if you want to split hairs.
-  I've told 'em!

196
00:14:43,170 --> 00:14:46,603
Proper sensation! They've put two men
on guard over it. Found anything?

197
00:14:46,722 --> 00:14:48,923
Plenty.
Do you know whose crest this is?

198
00:14:49,037 --> 00:14:50,595
- No.
- The Duke of Burgundy.

199
00:14:50,713 --> 00:14:53,317
- Who's he? Frenchman?
- This chap here.

200
00:14:53,426 --> 00:14:55,112
Burgundy was a country on its own
in his day.

201
00:14:55,222 --> 00:14:57,826
Well, what was he doing leaving his
stuff lying around in Miramont Place?

202
00:14:57,936 --> 00:15:01,968
Well, that's what we're trying to ferret out.
You can help. Here, take this.

203
00:15:02,087 --> 00:15:04,767
Look up "Burgundy, Grand Duke of".

204
00:15:07,554 --> 00:15:09,395
Miramont House.

205
00:15:09,509 --> 00:15:11,307
- This sounds promising.
-  Mm.

206
00:15:11,425 --> 00:15:16,983
"Destroyed by fire in 1490,
the property of Maurice de Charolais."

207
00:15:17,091 --> 00:15:19,216
- He's got the right sort of name.
- Yeah.

208
00:15:19,327 --> 00:15:22,563
Do you hear that, Frank?
If you find any mention of Maurice de...

209
00:15:23,996 --> 00:15:25,761
Frank.

210
00:15:26,829 --> 00:15:28,867
Really, Frank.

211
00:15:28,984 --> 00:15:30,869
Oh, I'm sorry.

212
00:15:30,979 --> 00:15:32,298
Butjust think of it.

213
00:15:32,416 --> 00:15:36,371
A saltwater fish that can blow itself up
to three times its own size.

214
00:15:36,486 --> 00:15:39,647
Don't you realise what this means?
It's history.

215
00:15:39,759 --> 00:15:42,124
History, my foot. It's money!

216
00:15:51,372 --> 00:15:52,658
Over this way a bit.

217
00:16:04,582 --> 00:16:06,663
And what are your plans for the future,
Mr Pemberton'?

218
00:16:06,776 --> 00:16:08,422
Oh, I don't know, maybe I'll retire,

219
00:16:08,533 --> 00:16:11,769
sail around the world in my own yacht
with a cargo of beautiful girls.

220
00:16:11,885 --> 00:16:15,481
Oh, hark at him!
Seasick on the Serpentine!

221
00:16:15,596 --> 00:16:18,833
I suppose I'll get something out of it.
I'm not counting my chickens yet, though.

222
00:16:18,949 --> 00:16:21,793
- Oh, well, thanks for the story.
- You're welcome.

223
00:16:21,901 --> 00:16:23,863
Gosh. Smashing.

224
00:16:23,977 --> 00:16:25,938
Yeah, it is. 17 and 9.

225
00:16:26,051 --> 00:16:29,484
That's all right. Have you heard
the inquest is fixed for tomorrow?

226
00:16:29,604 --> 00:16:30,846
Inquest? Who's dead?

227
00:16:30,960 --> 00:16:32,486
There's always an inquest
on treasure trove.

228
00:16:32,597 --> 00:16:34,514
The coroner has to sort out
the different claims.

229
00:16:34,632 --> 00:16:37,477
Oh, that shouldn't take him long.
After all, I found the stuff.

230
00:16:37,585 --> 00:16:40,582
But there was certain others
instrumental, wasn't there?

231
00:16:40,698 --> 00:16:43,139
- You've got to take that into account.
- How do you mean?

232
00:16:43,252 --> 00:16:47,088
Well, er... if Benny here
hadn't set that wheel rolling...

233
00:16:51,473 --> 00:16:54,513
Now, don't you try and come it over me.
You set it off. I saw you.

234
00:16:54,626 --> 00:16:57,787
- You weren't there.
- Call your own father a liar, would you?

235
00:16:57,898 --> 00:17:01,734
- OK, OK, I did it.
- Good boy.

236
00:17:01,848 --> 00:17:03,646
Come on, Charlie boy.

237
00:17:03,764 --> 00:17:07,120
You can tell me.
Mum won't be cross.

238
00:17:09,790 --> 00:17:13,550
- Don't want a sweet.
- You'll have a sweet and like it!

239
00:17:15,856 --> 00:17:18,973
So, you admit quite frankly
that the explosion of the bomb

240
00:17:19,089 --> 00:17:22,805
was solely due to this thoughtless
action of yours and yours alone?

241
00:17:22,920 --> 00:17:25,001
Yes, sir.

242
00:17:25,115 --> 00:17:26,553
Well, well!

243
00:17:26,671 --> 00:17:28,677
After nine years
as coroner of this district,

244
00:17:28,786 --> 00:17:32,022
I find this a new
and most refreshing experience.

245
00:17:32,138 --> 00:17:33,980
I congratulate the parents of Pimlico

246
00:17:34,094 --> 00:17:36,655
on such a fine crop
of exceptionally honest youngsters.

247
00:17:39,122 --> 00:17:43,797
That seems to dispose of the evidence
as to the finding of this treasure.

248
00:17:43,911 --> 00:17:47,431
There remains one further important duty
before the court.

249
00:17:47,543 --> 00:17:50,583
We must now establish
to whom it belongs.

250
00:17:50,695 --> 00:17:54,412
I understand that the old parchments
provide valuable evidence on this point.

251
00:17:54,526 --> 00:17:57,207
We will now hear
the translation of that document

252
00:17:57,320 --> 00:18:00,197
from Professor Hatton-Jones
of London University.

253
00:18:02,987 --> 00:18:06,344
Oh, I'm so sorry.

254
00:18:09,812 --> 00:18:12,209
I understand
that Professor Hatton-Jones

255
00:18:12,326 --> 00:18:15,279
has successfully established
the original ownership of this treasure.

256
00:18:15,398 --> 00:18:16,521
Yes, indeed.

257
00:18:16,636 --> 00:18:19,077
It belongs to the Duchy of Burgundy,

258
00:18:19,189 --> 00:18:22,186
being vested in the person
of the Duke Charles...

259
00:18:22,302 --> 00:18:24,623
Who, I believe, died in 1477?

260
00:18:24,737 --> 00:18:29,369
If we are to believe Basin,
Reiffenburg, Gollut and Schmel.

261
00:18:29,485 --> 00:18:31,883
In fact, according
to all the major historians,

262
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:34,364
he was killed at the Battle of Nancy.

263
00:18:34,475 --> 00:18:37,831
But with the aid
of this most exciting document,

264
00:18:37,946 --> 00:18:40,508
I am now able to change
the course of history.

265
00:18:40,620 --> 00:18:42,940
Would you mind explaining
your point more fully?

266
00:18:45,808 --> 00:18:47,966
Picture a battlefield.

267
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:56,465
9,481 frozen corpses are all that
remains of Burgundy's pride.

268
00:18:56,583 --> 00:18:58,861
The Duke himself lies slain among them.

269
00:18:58,977 --> 00:19:04,252
This poor naked body,
robbed by harpies, bitten by wolves,

270
00:19:04,365 --> 00:19:06,523
the visage battered beyond recognition,

271
00:19:06,640 --> 00:19:10,879
this they accept as the last
earthly remains of Charles VII,

272
00:19:10,990 --> 00:19:14,542
Duke of Burgundy,
last of the line of Charolais.

273
00:19:15,579 --> 00:19:17,617
Do they judge correctly?

274
00:19:17,734 --> 00:19:20,927
Is this indeed the cadaver
of Charles the Rash?

275
00:19:21,047 --> 00:19:22,365
Ha-ha!

276
00:19:22,483 --> 00:19:25,916
If so, then I am Joan of Arc.

277
00:19:29,188 --> 00:19:30,353
I see.

278
00:19:30,464 --> 00:19:33,504
Then it is your contention
that the historians were wrong,

279
00:19:33,618 --> 00:19:35,418
that the Duke of Burgundy
escaped with his life?

280
00:19:35,493 --> 00:19:39,045
Yes! Charles the Rash lives on.

281
00:19:39,164 --> 00:19:42,357
With the missing portion
of the Burgundian treasure,

282
00:19:42,477 --> 00:19:44,994
he has fled to an unknown refuge.

283
00:19:45,111 --> 00:19:50,189
Unknown for 500 years,
but known at last today!

284
00:19:51,176 --> 00:19:53,422
Miramont House, Pimlico!

285
00:20:00,994 --> 00:20:02,836
Now, it has always been known

286
00:20:02,950 --> 00:20:05,870
that Miramont House was occupied
by a Burgundian nobleman

287
00:20:05,982 --> 00:20:07,987
styling himself
the Count Maurice de Charolais.

288
00:20:08,098 --> 00:20:12,250
With the help of this document,
I now intend to prove

289
00:20:12,367 --> 00:20:14,449
that Maurice de Charolais
and the Duke of Burgundy

290
00:20:14,563 --> 00:20:15,805
were one and the same person.

291
00:20:15,919 --> 00:20:20,910
For it is a Royal Charter
signed by King Edward IV,

292
00:20:21,028 --> 00:20:23,469
making the Duke
not only a grant of Miramont House,

293
00:20:23,581 --> 00:20:27,733
but decreeing that the entire estate
shall be recognised henceforth

294
00:20:27,852 --> 00:20:29,290
as Burgundian soil.

295
00:20:29,408 --> 00:20:31,653
Now, Edward IV
would never have made such a grant...

296
00:20:31,762 --> 00:20:34,247
Er... excuse me, Professor.

297
00:20:34,356 --> 00:20:36,601
Are you implying that this treasure
does not belong to the crown?

298
00:20:36,711 --> 00:20:41,190
Oh, no, it belongs to the people
in the area covered by the old estate,

299
00:20:41,300 --> 00:20:45,495
since this charter specifically
makes them natives of Burgundy.

300
00:20:45,610 --> 00:20:48,334
Do you mean that these Londoners
are technically Burgundians?

301
00:20:48,444 --> 00:20:52,803
Indubitably. This Royal Charter
has never been repealed.

302
00:20:52,913 --> 00:20:54,798
It is as valid today

303
00:20:54,909 --> 00:20:58,222
as on the day it was signed
by the founder of the House of York.

304
00:20:58,341 --> 00:21:02,177
Blimey. I'm a foreigner.

305
00:21:02,292 --> 00:21:04,973
It would be difficult to exaggerate

306
00:21:05,086 --> 00:21:08,922
the enormous importance
of this document...

307
00:21:21,926 --> 00:21:24,727
- Looks like a fine weekend.
- Yes, sir.

308
00:21:30,027 --> 00:21:32,228
You'll be back.

309
00:21:38,408 --> 00:21:41,601
Miramont Place. Now, come on,
step lively, all you aliens.

310
00:21:41,721 --> 00:21:45,197
- Belgrave Road?
- No, lady, we're going to England.

311
00:21:55,089 --> 00:21:56,812
I'm sorry, sir, I wasn't expecting you.

312
00:21:56,925 --> 00:22:01,720
Wix, it seems that my last visit here
failed to make any impression on you.

313
00:22:01,834 --> 00:22:03,796
Or am I mistaken?

314
00:22:04,588 --> 00:22:06,746
Perhaps you did receive
Head Office sanction

315
00:22:06,862 --> 00:22:09,347
to admit the press
to one of our strongrooms.

316
00:22:09,456 --> 00:22:12,573
No, sir, but it...
it all happened so quickly, I...

317
00:22:12,689 --> 00:22:15,173
You've answered my question.
That's enough.

318
00:22:15,282 --> 00:22:17,887
I don't wish to pursue the matter.

319
00:22:17,997 --> 00:22:19,958
I shall have to advise Head Office
to arrange for your transfer

320
00:22:20,071 --> 00:22:21,390
to one of our country branches.

321
00:22:21,508 --> 00:22:23,753
Transfer? Oh, no, sir.

322
00:22:23,863 --> 00:22:26,304
L...l could never settle down
anywhere else.

323
00:22:26,417 --> 00:22:28,334
This is my home.
I... I've lived here all my life.

324
00:22:28,452 --> 00:22:30,413
I was born here.

325
00:22:31,205 --> 00:22:33,287
In Burgundy.

326
00:22:33,401 --> 00:22:35,362
You can't throw me out
of my own country.

327
00:22:35,476 --> 00:22:38,909
Don't be absurd, man. If you seriously
think that an obscure part of the law...

328
00:22:39,028 --> 00:22:41,752
Obscure or not, legally,
this is Burgundy.

329
00:22:41,861 --> 00:22:44,542
Head Office no longer has
any jurisdiction over this bank.

330
00:22:46,410 --> 00:22:48,088
This is my bank.

331
00:23:15,064 --> 00:23:17,189
I reckon two pounds will cover this.

332
00:23:17,299 --> 00:23:20,251
Hey, how many in your litter?
You need 40 ration books for that lot.

333
00:23:20,372 --> 00:23:23,130
Ration books'? This is Burgundy.

334
00:23:23,924 --> 00:23:25,765
Burgundy!

335
00:23:29,630 --> 00:23:31,711
You still got that blouse?

336
00:23:31,825 --> 00:23:34,865
- Fiddling coupons, then?
- Coupons? This is Burgundy.

337
00:23:40,445 --> 00:23:42,004
Ah!

338
00:23:42,840 --> 00:23:45,684
What do you want to queue for?
This is Burgundy!

339
00:23:48,427 --> 00:23:50,380
Now, then, now then!
Five to two, Full Moon.

340
00:23:50,462 --> 00:23:54,374
Now, come on. Who wants a bet? The oldest
firm in Burgundy. What's that, sir?

341
00:23:54,493 --> 00:23:58,645
Yes, your export department.
This is Burgundy.

342
00:23:58,763 --> 00:24:00,964
Burgundy! Burgundy!

343
00:24:02,515 --> 00:24:04,312
Drink up, Mr Wix.
Where's your patriotism?

344
00:24:04,430 --> 00:24:07,743
Sorry, but I've just been making
a rough estimate of our national assets.

345
00:24:07,862 --> 00:24:11,578
Crowns and ducats
to the value of£18,200.

346
00:24:11,693 --> 00:24:13,774
Pitchers, goblets and ewers
to the value of...

347
00:24:13,888 --> 00:24:17,049
- What's ewers?
- Mine's a pint.

348
00:24:17,160 --> 00:24:18,882
That's very good.

349
00:24:18,996 --> 00:24:20,282
Anyway, I estimate the total

350
00:24:20,392 --> 00:24:22,637
to be somewhere
in the neighbourhood of£100,000.

351
00:24:22,748 --> 00:24:24,993
Cor, that's about 1,000 nicker apiece,
ain't it?

352
00:24:25,102 --> 00:24:27,979
- I'll send Charlie to Eton.
- I'm gonna have a saltwater aquarium.

353
00:24:28,095 --> 00:24:29,217
Just a minute.

354
00:24:29,332 --> 00:24:32,449
I doubt whether individual claims can be
made to treasure vested in a community.

355
00:24:32,565 --> 00:24:34,047
Oh, I knew there'd be a catch in it.

356
00:24:34,161 --> 00:24:36,318
Whatever happens to the treasure,
that piece of land is ours.

357
00:24:36,435 --> 00:24:37,874
I think I know what's coming.

358
00:24:37,992 --> 00:24:40,433
Well, why not?
It's part of Burgundy now.

359
00:24:40,546 --> 00:24:43,063
About time we gave the kids a break.
We can have a go tomorrow.

360
00:24:43,180 --> 00:24:46,025
Let's turn the old static water tank
into a swimming pool, for a start.

361
00:24:46,133 --> 00:24:47,452
Hear, hear!

362
00:24:47,569 --> 00:24:51,841
- Here's to the Burgundy Lido!
- Hear, hear!

363
00:24:51,960 --> 00:24:54,118
All very laudable, no doubt,
but where are your returns?

364
00:24:54,235 --> 00:24:55,837
The real benefit to the community

365
00:24:55,950 --> 00:24:58,347
would be some scheme
for stimulating local trade

366
00:24:58,464 --> 00:25:00,665
- and launching new enterprises.
- That's what I say.

367
00:25:00,779 --> 00:25:02,261
Time, ladies and gentlemen, please.

368
00:25:02,376 --> 00:25:05,689
Here, what do you mean, time?
Where do you think we are, in England?

369
00:25:07,324 --> 00:25:09,885
No licensing laws here, my lad.
Isn't that so, Mr Garland?

370
00:25:09,998 --> 00:25:12,602
Yeah, that's right.
We close when I say.

371
00:25:12,711 --> 00:25:14,433
Not even a music license?

372
00:25:15,665 --> 00:25:17,671
You heard what the gentleman said.

373
00:25:32,825 --> 00:25:35,026
- He's better than Hutch.
- Much.

374
00:25:50,265 --> 00:25:51,987
Oh, Mr Hu...

375
00:26:13,491 --> 00:26:16,565
- How about a breath of fresh air?
- I think it's a bit too hot for walking.

376
00:26:16,683 --> 00:26:19,800
<i>I</i> I don't want to set the world

377
00:26:19,916 --> 00:26:23,872
J On fire

378
00:26:25,263 --> 00:26:27,944
<i>J</i> I just want to start

379
00:26:28,775 --> 00:26:32,328
<i>J</i> A little flame in your heart

380
00:26:35,080 --> 00:26:41,794
<i>J</i> In my heart I have but one desire...

381
00:26:44,818 --> 00:26:47,695
Not bad, that boy of yours.
He'd be worth 20 quid a week to you.

382
00:26:47,811 --> 00:26:49,937
- Yeah, I'll put him up a dollar.
- Hark at him.

383
00:26:50,046 --> 00:26:53,762
A dollar rise for the poor little perisher.
Skin a maggot, you would.

384
00:26:53,877 --> 00:26:56,917
- You keep a civil tongue in your head!
- Now, then! Now, then, now, then!

385
00:26:57,030 --> 00:27:00,070
- What's going on here?
- Nothing you can do about it, cock!

386
00:27:00,183 --> 00:27:02,548
That's right. You've said it right.

387
00:27:02,657 --> 00:27:05,818
You're in a foreign country now, Ted.
Drink when you like.

388
00:27:10,120 --> 00:27:11,842
Right. Mine's a pint.

389
00:27:17,543 --> 00:27:18,829
Spiller!

390
00:27:18,939 --> 00:27:21,576
Clear this place.
Go home, all you people.

391
00:27:22,730 --> 00:27:24,931
You're suspended from duty.

392
00:27:27,160 --> 00:27:30,157
Right, I'll have another pint.

393
00:27:31,431 --> 00:27:33,556
I'm going to take proceedings
against you, Mr Garland.

394
00:27:33,665 --> 00:27:35,986
Your identity card, please.

395
00:27:41,088 --> 00:27:43,812
Passing of betting slips
strictly prohibited.

396
00:27:45,039 --> 00:27:49,071
Come to think of it,
I shan't need this any more either.

397
00:27:50,666 --> 00:27:53,543
That's the stuff. Scrap 'em all.

398
00:27:53,659 --> 00:27:56,295
Stop it! Stop it, you idiots!

399
00:27:56,412 --> 00:27:58,418
Mr Wix, you're a responsible man.
Can't you do something?

400
00:27:58,527 --> 00:28:00,249
Certainly.

401
00:28:00,882 --> 00:28:04,435
- This is a job for Scotland Yard.
- Whitehall 1212.

402
00:28:04,553 --> 00:28:07,954
<i>J</i> Knees up, Mother Brown
Knees up, Mother Brown

403
00:28:08,066 --> 00:28:11,705
I Knees up, knees up, get those
knees up, knees up, Mother Brown...

404
00:28:11,816 --> 00:28:14,421
'...question of Pimlico. No.'
 'The Minister's out of town.'

405
00:28:14,531 --> 00:28:15,533
'Hello?'
 'Pimlico.'

406
00:28:15,647 --> 00:28:17,869
'Put this call through
to the Home Office, please.'

407
00:28:17,922 --> 00:28:19,045
'Yes, Pimlico.'
 'No, Burgundy.'

408
00:28:19,160 --> 00:28:21,361
'Pimlico.'
 'Clear the line. Priority call.'

409
00:28:25,465 --> 00:28:27,590
Back again, sir?

410
00:28:36,280 --> 00:28:39,200
Mr Straker of the Foreign Office.

411
00:28:41,907 --> 00:28:44,185
- Have you been here all night?
- Hm.

412
00:28:44,301 --> 00:28:46,743
- What's this Pimlico stuff?
- Top priority.

413
00:28:46,856 --> 00:28:50,016
- The old man wants immediate action.
- Well, what are you gonna do?

414
00:28:50,128 --> 00:28:52,448
Well, I thought that as the treasure
was originally spoils of battle,

415
00:28:52,562 --> 00:28:55,515
- I'd pass it on to the War Office.
- Oh, they wouldn't touch it.

416
00:28:56,673 --> 00:28:59,909
You see, technically,
these Burgundians are aliens.

417
00:29:00,025 --> 00:29:02,467
Aliens? Well, then, it's your pigeon.

418
00:29:02,579 --> 00:29:05,183
No, no, they're undesirable aliens
so it's your pigeon.

419
00:29:05,293 --> 00:29:07,091
I suppose you'll have to boot them
out of the country.

420
00:29:07,209 --> 00:29:09,573
Yes, but it's their own country.

421
00:29:21,056 --> 00:29:23,780
- There's your ten, Dad.
- All right.

422
00:29:33,388 --> 00:29:36,232
Black market eggs!
Black market butter!

423
00:29:36,340 --> 00:29:38,258
Lovely black market butter!

424
00:29:38,376 --> 00:29:43,170
Come on, ladies!
Give the old man a treat! It's lovely!

425
00:29:43,284 --> 00:29:46,401
All the grub you want
for a pre-war breakfast!

426
00:29:47,675 --> 00:29:50,475
Nylons! Genuine stolen nylons!

427
00:29:50,587 --> 00:29:53,224
Guinea a pair! Fully fashioned!

428
00:29:53,341 --> 00:29:56,218
Get these lovely nylons!

429
00:29:59,767 --> 00:30:01,772
Come on, ladies!

430
00:30:04,875 --> 00:30:07,152
Turn it up! I'm coming!

431
00:30:09,464 --> 00:30:13,256
- Good morning, Mrs Randall.
- You gone barmy? It's Sunday.

432
00:30:13,375 --> 00:30:16,731
Special delivery.
Two dozen boxes export silks.

433
00:30:18,084 --> 00:30:20,569
That's right. Come on, let's have 'em.

434
00:30:25,387 --> 00:30:28,624
Black market bacon!
Off the ration!

435
00:30:28,740 --> 00:30:33,338
Hey, off the ration! Black market bacon!
Come and get your bacon!

436
00:30:50,250 --> 00:30:52,734
- Mind your back, Ma.
- Hey, no parking here!

437
00:30:52,843 --> 00:30:54,489
Who says so?

438
00:30:54,600 --> 00:30:56,561
- Hi, you, get moving.
- Get out of it.

439
00:30:56,674 --> 00:30:59,116
- Oh, it's like that, is it?
- Go on, you silly old slob.

440
00:30:59,229 --> 00:31:02,149
- Hawker's license.
- You want to make something of it?

441
00:31:02,262 --> 00:31:04,300
- Go on, sock him one, Harry.
- We'll see about that.

442
00:31:04,417 --> 00:31:06,182
It's no use, Ted.
They've all read the papers.

443
00:31:06,292 --> 00:31:07,851
Here comes Mr Pemberton.

444
00:31:10,643 --> 00:31:14,359
Go on, get out of it!
We're gonna start digging here.

445
00:31:25,209 --> 00:31:26,495
What's going on?

446
00:31:26,605 --> 00:31:29,362
Looks to me like the annual outing
from Dartmoor.

447
00:31:29,478 --> 00:31:31,854
Ah, don't worry. I'm seeing to it.
Just going to ring the nick.

448
00:31:37,181 --> 00:31:40,254
- Ah, the Chief Constable of Burgundy.
- Sir, about last night...

449
00:31:40,373 --> 00:31:42,138
You'd better get yourself a new uniform.

450
00:31:42,249 --> 00:31:44,407
This area is out of bounds
to the Metropolitan Police.

451
00:31:44,524 --> 00:31:46,649
- What?
- Yes, Mr Pemberton.

452
00:31:46,759 --> 00:31:49,594
Home Office has just confirmed what
you were all shouting about last night.

453
00:31:49,632 --> 00:31:51,430
It was a bit of nonsense.
We'd all had a few.

454
00:31:51,548 --> 00:31:53,389
Yes, and Whitehall's got the headache.

455
00:31:53,503 --> 00:31:55,465
And until they can decide
which department is responsible,

456
00:31:55,578 --> 00:31:57,223
our orders are to keep out of Burgundy.

457
00:31:57,334 --> 00:31:59,819
And in the meantime, I suppose, nobody
cares if we all get our throats cut?

458
00:31:59,928 --> 00:32:01,410
I'm sorry,
I'm just telling you the position.

459
00:32:01,525 --> 00:32:02,963
Oh, we're not having that.

460
00:32:03,081 --> 00:32:06,078
We've all paid our rates.
We're entitled to police protection.

461
00:32:10,304 --> 00:32:12,385
Gregg. Who?

462
00:32:12,499 --> 00:32:14,580
Pemberton of Pimlico.

463
00:32:14,694 --> 00:32:17,975
No, sir, no. Nobody can help you
unless you have delegatory powers.

464
00:32:18,086 --> 00:32:20,331
Delegatory powers? H m -

465
00:32:20,441 --> 00:32:24,157
All right. But in plain English, I'm
speaking for all of us who live here.

466
00:32:24,272 --> 00:32:27,029
