503
00:35:22,738 --> 00:35:25,299
That settles it.

504
00:35:25,412 --> 00:35:28,093
Mrs Randall, Mr Spiller and yours truly.

505
00:35:32,635 --> 00:35:34,552
Now I'd better ring up Whitehall
right away.

506
00:35:34,670 --> 00:35:36,828
What's that? What's going on?

507
00:35:36,945 --> 00:35:39,669
They're gonna sell out,
gonna give the place back to England.

508
00:35:39,779 --> 00:35:42,264
Mr Pemberton, just a minute.

509
00:35:42,373 --> 00:35:44,814
If you hand Burgundy back,
they'll claim our treasure with it.

510
00:35:44,927 --> 00:35:46,453
Oh, we can come to terms about that.

511
00:35:46,563 --> 00:35:48,525
The important thing
is to get law and order here.

512
00:35:48,639 --> 00:35:52,235
Can't have the place turned into a spiv's paradise.
Hello, Mr Straker, please.

513
00:35:52,350 --> 00:35:55,347
What about us business people?
This is our big chance, ain't it?

514
00:35:55,463 --> 00:35:57,904
- Hear, hear!
- I'm in business too, aren't I?

515
00:35:58,016 --> 00:36:00,653
That doesn't mean I want
to be murdered in my bed.

516
00:36:02,206 --> 00:36:04,527
Shh. Shh, quiet!

517
00:36:04,641 --> 00:36:08,913
Hello? Er... Mr Straker?
My name is Arthur Pemberton.

518
00:36:09,031 --> 00:36:10,153
L...I'd like to report that

519
00:36:10,268 --> 00:36:13,069
we have now a formed a representative
committee of the people of Burgundy.

520
00:36:13,182 --> 00:36:15,383
I see.

521
00:36:15,496 --> 00:36:18,340
Yes. Oh, yes, yes,
I am in touch with Mr Gregg.

522
00:36:18,450 --> 00:36:21,806
But a rather abstruse
constitutional issue has now arisen,

523
00:36:21,921 --> 00:36:24,722
and I'm afraid we shall have to pass
it on to the Law Offices Department.

524
00:36:24,834 --> 00:36:29,553
Now, see here, sir. For all we know, that
might take weeks. All right, months.

525
00:36:29,663 --> 00:36:32,028
Hello? Hello?

526
00:36:32,137 --> 00:36:34,218
Ah, can you beat that?

527
00:36:34,332 --> 00:36:36,174
First of all, they say
we must have a committee.

528
00:36:36,288 --> 00:36:38,206
Now they say it can only be
officially recognised

529
00:36:38,323 --> 00:36:41,800
if appointed in accordance with
the electoral laws of ancient Burgundy.

530
00:36:41,915 --> 00:36:43,953
Well, that seems to settle things.

531
00:36:44,070 --> 00:36:46,315
Unless, of course, somebody present
happens to be familiar

532
00:36:46,424 --> 00:36:48,342
with the electoral laws
of ancient Burgundy.

533
00:36:48,460 --> 00:36:51,217
But certainly.

534
00:36:51,333 --> 00:36:53,817
It was the custom
for the Duke of Burgundy himself

535
00:36:53,927 --> 00:36:56,247
to elect a council of two sheriffs,
one burgess,

536
00:36:56,361 --> 00:36:58,127
and one hoof man
or captain of the guard.

537
00:36:58,237 --> 00:36:59,479
Who might you be?

538
00:36:59,594 --> 00:37:01,599
My name is Sebastien de Charolais,

539
00:37:01,709 --> 00:37:03,986
and I come from Dijon,
capital of ancient Burgundy.

540
00:37:04,103 --> 00:37:07,459
Mm. Only the Duke himself
can appoint a council,

541
00:37:07,575 --> 00:37:09,101
and <i>as</i> there is no such person...

542
00:37:09,212 --> 00:37:13,887
Oh, but you're wrong. There is
such person. I am the Duke of Burgundy.

543
00:37:14,001 --> 00:37:15,439
No!

544
00:37:15,557 --> 00:37:19,077
I am the direct descendant of Maurice
de Charolais, who came here in 1477.

545
00:37:19,188 --> 00:37:23,667
Therefore I am the heir to the title.
I hope you don't mind.

546
00:37:23,778 --> 00:37:28,094
Oh, no, no. I mean, well... l mean,
well, it's a bit of a turn-up, isn't it?

547
00:37:28,208 --> 00:37:32,643
Here is my evidence. These documents
have been in my family for centuries.

548
00:37:32,757 --> 00:37:37,268
I have always thought they were
of no value, just an amusing curiosity.

549
00:37:37,386 --> 00:37:40,426
But when I read about your discovery,
I said to myself...

550
00:37:42,414 --> 00:37:44,376
Yes, I bet you did.

551
00:37:45,647 --> 00:37:48,251
Hm. Of course,
you want them to be examined.

552
00:37:48,361 --> 00:37:50,126
Oh, indubitably.

553
00:37:55,863 --> 00:37:57,825
Hello, Pemberton's?

554
00:37:57,939 --> 00:37:59,901
Oh, yes.

555
00:38:00,014 --> 00:38:04,405
What, can't he eat anything? Oh, poor
little fellow. Must be this heat.

556
00:38:04,524 --> 00:38:07,008
Yes, all right.
I'll have something for him.

557
00:38:07,117 --> 00:38:10,234
Send him round the back door, will you?
Thank you. Goodbye.

558
00:38:10,350 --> 00:38:11,995
Mrs Wilson.

559
00:38:12,785 --> 00:38:13,863
Sorry, folks.

560
00:38:13,982 --> 00:38:15,584
Well, there seems
nothing more to be done

561
00:38:15,697 --> 00:38:17,461
until this gentleman's claims
are investigated.

562
00:38:17,493 --> 00:38:19,618
So, all we can do
is to adjourn the meeting.

563
00:38:19,729 --> 00:38:21,974
- Hear, hear!
-  Hear, hear!

564
00:38:26,194 --> 00:38:29,071
- I am afraid I am a great nuisance.
- No, no, no. Not at all.

565
00:38:29,187 --> 00:38:32,543
- You may be the very man we want.
- I hope so.

566
00:38:32,659 --> 00:38:34,697
<i>Au revoir, madame.</i>

567
00:38:35,691 --> 00:38:37,097
<i>Au revoir.</i>

568
00:38:37,208 --> 00:38:40,401
Mademoiselle, it occurs to me that I ought
to know something about my dukedom.

569
00:38:40,520 --> 00:38:43,277
Would you care to show me
a little of this new Burgundy?

570
00:38:43,393 --> 00:38:45,311
Well, I could do
with a breath of fresh air.

571
00:38:45,429 --> 00:38:47,630
Alors, we go.

572
00:38:47,744 --> 00:38:49,509
So gay and exciting.

573
00:38:49,619 --> 00:38:52,464
So different
from our dreary French towns.

574
00:38:53,290 --> 00:39:00,439
J I just want to start
a little flame in your heart

575
00:39:02,748 --> 00:39:08,306
<i>J</i> In my heart I have but one desire...

576
00:39:11,967 --> 00:39:13,928
Professor Hatton-Jones?

577
00:39:14,042 --> 00:39:17,159
Oh. Yes, it is, very urgent.

578
00:39:18,393 --> 00:39:19,995
When?

579
00:39:21,386 --> 00:39:23,064
Oh.

580
00:39:23,182 --> 00:39:25,699
No, all right.
I'll ring again in the morning.

581
00:39:27,451 --> 00:39:30,209
'Today,
after reading in the Sunday papers,

582
00:39:30,325 --> 00:39:34,716
'that the laws of the United Kingdom
cannot be held to operate in Burgundy,

583
00:39:34,834 --> 00:39:36,033
'from an early hour,

584
00:39:36,151 --> 00:39:40,303
'London Transport officials have had to
deal with crowds of Cup Tie dimensions

585
00:39:40,422 --> 00:39:43,658
'on all tube and bus routes to Pimlico.

586
00:39:43,774 --> 00:39:45,691
'Here is an official announcement

587
00:39:45,809 --> 00:39:49,601
'issued from Whitehall
within the last hour.

588
00:39:49,720 --> 00:39:51,921
'Pending the introduction
of a new Act of Parliament

589
00:39:52,035 --> 00:39:53,832
'the public are earnestly asked

590
00:39:53,950 --> 00:39:56,947
'not to exploit the prevailing
currency leak in Pimlico

591
00:39:57,063 --> 00:39:59,744
'and to refrain from entering
the area involved.'

592
00:39:59,856 --> 00:40:01,964
'Should this appeal be disregarded,

593
00:40:01,972 --> 00:40:04,097
'the Government may be
reluctantly compelled

594
00:40:04,206 --> 00:40:06,648
'to apply sterner measures forthwith.'

595
00:40:08,396 --> 00:40:10,238
Talk, talk, talk!

596
00:40:10,352 --> 00:40:12,717
Why can't they do something?

597
00:40:31,144 --> 00:40:34,141
- Your coffee, sir.
- Thank you. Pour it in, please.

598
00:40:34,257 --> 00:40:36,937
You know, your England
is a most remarkable nation.

599
00:40:37,050 --> 00:40:40,244
Everywhere else, governments
command, scream, shout,

600
00:40:40,362 --> 00:40:43,718
but here it just has to ask people
politely to stay away and they do.

601
00:40:57,842 --> 00:40:59,564
Ha-ha-ha!

602
00:40:59,678 --> 00:41:02,751
I still say a remarkable nation.

603
00:41:03,828 --> 00:41:06,868
Entrez.

604
00:41:06,981 --> 00:41:07,984
Come in!

605
00:41:10,851 --> 00:41:12,213
Good morning, sir.
I hope you'll pardon us for...

606
00:41:12,328 --> 00:41:13,767
I am the culprit.

607
00:41:13,885 --> 00:41:16,609
This is Professor Hatton-Jones
of the London University.

608
00:41:16,718 --> 00:41:21,393
The moment our good friend told me
the news, I was Arion, I was Zephyrus!

609
00:41:21,507 --> 00:41:24,188
Nothing could detain me
from instant communion

610
00:41:24,301 --> 00:41:26,862
with the living survivor
of the House of Charolais!

611
00:41:26,975 --> 00:41:29,133
Er... you have examined my documents?

612
00:41:29,249 --> 00:41:31,255
Oh, a cursory glance.

613
00:41:31,364 --> 00:41:35,396
Personally, I have no doubt at all
as to the question of your lineage.

614
00:41:35,514 --> 00:41:37,117
Forgive me, are you a bleeder?

615
00:41:37,231 --> 00:41:40,827
- I beg your pardon?
- Do you suffer from haemophilia?

616
00:41:40,942 --> 00:41:45,540
When you cut yourself,
do you bleed interminably?

617
00:41:45,651 --> 00:41:48,648
- No, I don't think so.
- Ah, a pity.

618
00:41:48,764 --> 00:41:51,206
It's in the family.
Definitely in the family.

619
00:41:51,318 --> 00:41:53,083
Oh, I am very sorry.

620
00:41:53,194 --> 00:41:56,067
- I don't want to hurry you, Professor, but...
- Oh, quite, quite! Ha-ha-ha!

621
00:41:56,147 --> 00:41:59,263
I mustn't embark on family matters
or I'll be here all day.

622
00:41:59,379 --> 00:42:01,744
I have to take these off
for a sulphate reaction test.

623
00:42:01,853 --> 00:42:03,859
I'll soon be back, though.
Depend on that.

624
00:42:03,969 --> 00:42:08,448
Now that I know you're truly extant,
I go away satisfied.

625
00:42:08,558 --> 00:42:10,955
Ha-ha! What Gollut would give
to be in my shoes!

626
00:42:11,072 --> 00:42:14,472
Ha! I could even put
Schmel in the shade!

627
00:42:21,169 --> 00:42:22,855
How long is this chemical test
going to take?

628
00:42:22,965 --> 00:42:26,441
- That's contingent on certain factors.
- Please hurry it up.

629
00:42:26,556 --> 00:42:29,117
If things go on like this much longer...

630
00:42:30,387 --> 00:42:32,588
What's happened now?
They're packing up.

631
00:42:32,702 --> 00:42:35,426
- What does this mean?
- I don't know.

632
00:42:37,810 --> 00:42:40,186
You'll have to take
your place in the queue, madam.

633
00:42:40,284 --> 00:42:43,640
What's the idea holding us up like this?
I got my dinner to cook.

634
00:42:57,684 --> 00:42:59,569
Ah, look at that.

635
00:42:59,679 --> 00:43:01,357
- Action at last.
- Yes.

636
00:43:01,475 --> 00:43:03,437
That'll keep the spivs out.

637
00:43:03,551 --> 00:43:05,348
Oh, er... Mr Pemberton.

638
00:43:05,466 --> 00:43:07,831
- Ah.
- Mr Pemberton.

639
00:43:07,940 --> 00:43:10,185
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

640
00:43:10,295 --> 00:43:13,772
This is Mr Bagshawe of the, er...
Board of Customs & Excise.

641
00:43:13,887 --> 00:43:15,420
He'd like to have a
word with you people.

642
00:43:15,443 --> 00:43:18,167
There are just a few things
I would like to explain.

643
00:43:18,277 --> 00:43:20,761
- If I might step over your frontier.
- By all means.

644
00:43:20,870 --> 00:43:23,790
I must congratulate you
on the speed with which you have...

645
00:43:23,903 --> 00:43:27,064
Oh, excuse me, Professor. This looks
like the solution to all our troubles.

646
00:43:27,176 --> 00:43:29,094
This way.

647
00:43:30,648 --> 00:43:32,654
In the line, please, madam.

648
00:43:40,265 --> 00:43:41,704
Have you anything to declare, madam?

649
00:43:41,822 --> 00:43:44,383
Any food stuff, livestock,
linen or cotton goods?

650
00:43:44,496 --> 00:43:48,135
I hardly think this is likely to include
the credentials of the Duke of Burgundy.

651
00:43:48,247 --> 00:43:51,887
Would you mind
opening that case, madam?

652
00:43:51,998 --> 00:43:56,837
This really is a big relief to us, I can tell you.
It's a very very clever bit of...

653
00:43:56,947 --> 00:44:00,619
- No, no, I think you're wrong.
- What's all that in aid of?

654
00:44:03,452 --> 00:44:05,751
- But we tore 'em up, I tell you!
- You let him have it, Dad!

655
00:44:05,847 --> 00:44:07,492
That's where we live, right there.

656
00:44:07,602 --> 00:44:10,163
It's merely part
of the Customs procedure.

657
00:44:10,276 --> 00:44:12,554
We naturally have to enforce
the immigration laws.

658
00:44:12,671 --> 00:44:14,676
You can't have the one
without the other.

659
00:44:14,786 --> 00:44:16,703
Yes, but...

660
00:44:16,821 --> 00:44:20,014
Frederick Albert Cowan Esquire. That's
me. Number four, Miramont Gardens.

661
00:44:20,133 --> 00:44:21,299
I am sorry, sir.

662
00:44:21,411 --> 00:44:24,091
The order specifies
that identity cards must be produced

663
00:44:24,203 --> 00:44:27,243
by residents who wish
to re-enter the street.

664
00:44:27,356 --> 00:44:29,514
Do you mean to say that
all of us who live in this street

665
00:44:29,631 --> 00:44:32,508
have got to go through that rigmarole
every time we want to leave our homes?

666
00:44:32,624 --> 00:44:34,509
Oh, for a month or two.

667
00:44:34,619 --> 00:44:36,228
After all,
pending a new Act of Parliament,

668
00:44:36,256 --> 00:44:38,054
this is technically foreign territory.

669
00:44:38,172 --> 00:44:39,730
Ha-ha-ha! Foreign territory!

670
00:44:39,848 --> 00:44:40,894
I suppose that means

671
00:44:41,005 --> 00:44:42,563
British subjects won't be allowed
to spend any money here.

672
00:44:42,681 --> 00:44:43,792
What about all our customers?

673
00:44:43,799 --> 00:44:45,118
You can't stop us earning
an honest living.

674
00:44:45,235 --> 00:44:46,960
I've never heard
such a lot of rot in my life.

675
00:44:47,070 --> 00:44:48,509
Don't blame me, ladies and gentlemen.

676
00:44:48,627 --> 00:44:51,188
Edward lV's the one
who made you foreigners.

677
00:44:51,301 --> 00:44:52,379
Here we go again!

678
00:44:52,498 --> 00:44:54,416
- You people make me tired.
- Order, order!

679
00:44:54,534 --> 00:44:56,735
Oh, shut up. Did you ever
hear such tripe in your life?

680
00:44:56,848 --> 00:44:58,527
- Now look here, sir!
- And you shut up too.

681
00:44:58,644 --> 00:45:02,436
All right, if that's the way Whitehall
want it, in future, we'll be foreigners.

682
00:45:02,555 --> 00:45:03,874
That's the stuff, Dad.

683
00:45:03,992 --> 00:45:07,348
We'll fight them in the tramlines,
we'll fight them in the local.

684
00:45:30,969 --> 00:45:33,008
Good evening, Professor.

685
00:45:33,124 --> 00:45:34,530
Oh, good evening.

686
00:45:34,641 --> 00:45:37,714
Your friends in Miramont Place
have got themselves into a nice mess.

687
00:45:37,833 --> 00:45:41,266
Poor souls.
The innocent victims of destiny.

688
00:45:41,385 --> 00:45:42,704
They started all this nonsense.

689
00:45:42,822 --> 00:45:44,261
Now they've got to put up
with the consequences.

690
00:45:44,378 --> 00:45:48,530
Ah, but will they?
The Burgundians are a fighting people.

691
00:45:48,648 --> 00:45:51,090
Consider what they did
against the might of Louis XI.

692
00:45:51,203 --> 00:45:54,199
I fail to see what this little mob
can do against the might of Britain.

693
00:45:56,191 --> 00:45:59,188
Oh! Get up, please.

694
00:45:59,303 --> 00:46:02,104
All passports. Passports ready, please.

695
00:46:02,217 --> 00:46:03,939
All hand luggage open, please.

696
00:46:04,052 --> 00:46:06,297
Time to make
your currency declarations, please.

697
00:46:06,407 --> 00:46:07,933
What the devil does this mean?

698
00:46:08,043 --> 00:46:09,961
The train is now
at the Burgundian frontier.

699
00:46:10,078 --> 00:46:12,236
A fighting people, Mr Bassett.

700
00:46:12,353 --> 00:46:15,906
Worthy successors
of the Knights of the Golden Fleece.

701
00:46:16,024 --> 00:46:17,627
Have you anything to declare, madam?

702
00:46:17,741 --> 00:46:20,106
Any food stuff, livestock,
linen or cotton goods?

703
00:46:20,215 --> 00:46:21,217
No.

704
00:46:21,332 --> 00:46:23,055
Any muskrats,
mealworms, motorcycles,

705
00:46:23,168 --> 00:46:25,533
hashish, prepared opium
or agricultural machinery?

706
00:46:25,642 --> 00:46:27,081
Oh!

707
00:46:29,912 --> 00:46:33,912
Have you any foreign currency?
English pounds? Traveller's cheques?

708
00:46:34,023 --> 00:46:37,336
- Suppose I have?
- I just wondered.

709
00:46:39,411 --> 00:46:42,255
No passage beyond this point
without passports. All passports.

710
00:46:42,363 --> 00:46:44,281
- Here is mine.
- Hm?

711
00:46:46,714 --> 00:46:49,111
What is it you... you... Baratooshe,

712
00:46:49,228 --> 00:46:50,906
er... Baratooshe,

713
00:46:51,024 --> 00:46:54,260
er... Baratooshe... United Kingdom!

714
00:47:09,062 --> 00:47:11,067
England, United Kingdom!

715
00:47:12,255 --> 00:47:16,526
All hand luggage ready for inspection,
please. Anything to declare?

716
00:47:16,644 --> 00:47:19,521
Anything to declare, sir? Any livestock,
foodstuff, linen or cotton goods?

717
00:47:19,637 --> 00:47:21,196
Rather!

718
00:47:30,572 --> 00:47:33,689
Come along.
Come along, please.

719
00:47:33,805 --> 00:47:37,477
All ready with your passports.
Get your passports out.

720
00:47:37,596 --> 00:47:40,037
So reminds me of the time
I visited the catacombs.

721
00:47:40,150 --> 00:47:42,188
Mr Pemberton, this is preposterous.

722
00:47:42,305 --> 00:47:43,831
Sorry, Mr Bassett.
We're a foreign country now.

723
00:47:43,941 --> 00:47:46,382
We can't allow tourists
without the usual formalities.

724
00:47:46,495 --> 00:47:47,695
Come along, sir, please.

725
00:47:47,812 --> 00:47:49,894
- Pass down the track.
- The Duke!

726
00:47:50,007 --> 00:47:53,646
- Oh, madam, is it proved?
- Beyond a title of a doubt.

727
00:47:53,758 --> 00:47:56,832
Yes, gentlemen, you see before you
the 18th Duke of Burgundy.

728
00:47:56,951 --> 00:47:59,315
Your liege lord, your sovereign!

729
00:48:07,048 --> 00:48:09,368
Floreat Burgundia!

730
00:48:09,482 --> 00:48:12,643
Stop that train!

731
00:48:54,378 --> 00:48:56,416
What are we going to tell the old man?

732
00:48:56,533 --> 00:48:58,015
Well, after this underground business,

733
00:48:58,129 --> 00:49:00,886
I doubt if he will give us
a chance to open our mouths.

734
00:49:01,002 --> 00:49:02,767
Soap.

735
00:49:04,514 --> 00:49:05,637
Were you issued with this?

736
00:49:05,752 --> 00:49:07,474
No, I pinched it
from the French Embassy.

737
00:49:07,587 --> 00:49:09,352
Oh. Ha-ha.

738
00:49:09,463 --> 00:49:13,060
This situation, though,
it's an absolute deadlock.

739
00:49:13,175 --> 00:49:14,777
Oh, no, not quite.

740
00:49:14,890 --> 00:49:17,964
Now that this Duke
has been officially recognised,

741
00:49:18,083 --> 00:49:19,642
we can at least talk to them.

742
00:49:19,759 --> 00:49:21,362
- Towel?
- The time for talk's past.

743
00:49:21,475 --> 00:49:24,036
Any more talk and we've had it.
We've got to do something.

744
00:49:24,149 --> 00:49:25,675
We've got to tell this Duke
where he gets off.

745
00:49:25,785 --> 00:49:28,585
Oh, well, I hope the old man
won't put me on to it.

746
00:49:28,698 --> 00:49:31,695
After all, this fellow's been made
a sort of king in a way.

747
00:49:31,811 --> 00:49:34,928
Yes. Probably having his coronation
at this very moment.

748
00:49:35,882 --> 00:49:39,402
Well, why don't you loosen your tie,
Your Grace?

749
00:49:39,514 --> 00:49:43,513
- I thought you'd be used to the heat.
- Well, it's never <i>as</i> bad <i>as</i> that in Dijon.

750
00:49:43,623 --> 00:49:46,424
All the same, I bet you'd rather
be there than couped up here.

751
00:49:46,537 --> 00:49:49,021
Why do you think it
so much nicer than Pimlico?

752
00:49:50,608 --> 00:49:52,689
I imagine it's a little more romantic.

753
00:49:52,803 --> 00:49:57,761
Oh, do you? What do you think
we would be doing in Dijon this evening?

754
00:49:58,868 --> 00:50:01,233
Well, we... we'd eat in the open

755
00:50:01,342 --> 00:50:05,418
and dance in the main square
under the trees.

756
00:50:06,571 --> 00:50:09,416
Then maybe we'd go for a little walk

757
00:50:09,524 --> 00:50:13,599
up one of those funny old
cobbled streets to the castle

758
00:50:14,632 --> 00:50:17,945
and when we reach the orange grove...

759
00:50:18,064 --> 00:50:21,258
we'd sit beneath the castle wall

760
00:50:22,813 --> 00:50:24,339
and watch the dawn come up.

761
00:50:24,449 --> 00:50:28,165
And, er...
in the cool morning breeze,

762
00:50:28,280 --> 00:50:31,757
maybe I would put my coat
around your shoulders

763
00:50:31,872 --> 00:50:33,833
and...

764
00:50:38,616 --> 00:50:40,219
<i>Hm.</i>

765
00:50:41,490 --> 00:50:44,367
Well, anyway,
I'm afraid Dijon is not a bit like that.

766
00:50:44,483 --> 00:50:47,599
We cannot dance in the main square because
of the trams which run all night,

767
00:50:47,715 --> 00:50:50,832
and, er... we cannot grow oranges
because it's too cold,

768
00:50:50,948 --> 00:50:54,544
and, er... where the castle was,
well, today there is a cement factory.

769
00:50:54,659 --> 00:50:56,544
Then it's just about <i>as</i> romantic
as Camden Town.

770
00:50:56,654 --> 00:50:59,139
Ah, but the people,
they make it different.

771
00:50:59,249 --> 00:51:03,249
You should see us at the vendange,
the, er... the wine harvest,

772
00:51:03,359 --> 00:51:05,364
when all over the country,
the peasants celebrate.

773
00:51:05,474 --> 00:51:10,269
And they are gay,
not... not drunk but very, very gay.

774
00:51:10,383 --> 00:51:13,980
And, er... well, I suppose
we would walk in the moonlight,

775
00:51:14,094 --> 00:51:16,100
through the sloping vineyards,

776
00:51:16,209 --> 00:51:21,168
and we would come to an old Roman
ruin called the Temple d'Amour,

777
00:51:21,278 --> 00:51:23,839
- Hm?
- The Temple of Love.

778
00:51:24,710 --> 00:51:28,709
I see. And there the walk ends
and I succumb to your gallant charm.

779
00:51:28,820 --> 00:51:32,373
Oh, no. No, no, no, no. Because my
intentions, they are most honourable.

780
00:51:32,492 --> 00:51:38,289
I would talk to you about my job
at the hotel, my income, my prospects,

781
00:51:38,398 --> 00:51:41,711
- No funny business at all?
- Absolutely none.

782
00:51:42,548 --> 00:51:44,586
- No'?
- No.

783
00:51:51,927 --> 00:51:53,605
Let's go in.

784
00:52:02,502 --> 00:52:05,575
Hi, you two! Hullo there!

785
00:52:05,695 --> 00:52:09,051
- What is it, Dad?
- Gentleman here to see the Duke!

786
00:52:09,167 --> 00:52:10,573
Oh.

787
00:52:11,681 --> 00:52:12,847
Well, I'm really glad.

788
00:52:12,958 --> 00:52:15,562
Course, I always knew you people would
have to recognise us sooner or later.

789
00:52:15,671 --> 00:52:18,036
- Ah, here is the Duke.
- Ah, Your Excellency.

790
00:52:18,146 --> 00:52:20,467
Allow me to present my credentials.

791
00:52:22,456 --> 00:52:25,692
But I'm not the ruler now.
No, they've asked me to form a cabinet.

792
00:52:25,808 --> 00:52:28,848
- <i>Oh, long live democracy!</i>
- <i>Vive l'Angleterre!</i>

793
00:52:28,960 --> 00:52:31,565
<i>- Vive la France!
- What next'?</i>

794
00:52:31,675 --> 00:52:35,347
Well, you will understand that after
today's incident on the underground,

795
00:52:35,466 --> 00:52:38,386
His Majesty's Government
does not feel inclined to negotiate

796
00:52:38,499 --> 00:52:39,495
with a pistol at its head.

797
00:52:39,576 --> 00:52:42,093
Now that we've come down to <i>brass</i>
tacks, I can guarantee there'll be no...

798
00:52:42,210 --> 00:52:45,927
His Majesty's Government has a traditional
dislike of unilateral guarantees.

799
00:52:46,041 --> 00:52:48,799
It has therefore felt itself compelled,
most reluctantly,

800
00:52:48,915 --> 00:52:51,073
to close the frontier
as from 10AM tomorrow.

801
00:52:51,190 --> 00:52:53,074
- Close the frontier?
- What about us?

802
00:52:53,185 --> 00:52:55,985
A church hall has been equipped
for the evacuation of all those who...

803
00:52:56,098 --> 00:52:57,297
- Church hall?
- Evacuation?

804
00:52:57,415 --> 00:52:58,777
What about our treasure?

805
00:52:58,891 --> 00:53:02,127
Well, for the time being, that can be
moved to the Bank of England.

806
00:53:02,243 --> 00:53:05,088
Oh, yeah?
Well, I'm not moving anyway.

807
00:53:05,197 --> 00:53:06,200
I beg your pardon?

808
00:53:06,314 --> 00:53:08,231
If the Nazis couldn't
drive me out of my home

809
00:53:08,349 --> 00:53:10,550
with all their bombs
and rockets and doodlebugs,

810
00:53:10,664 --> 00:53:12,146
you don't catch me packing up now!

811
00:53:12,261 --> 00:53:14,386
Hear, hear!

812
00:53:14,495 --> 00:53:17,132
I trust you realise that
the alternative is complete isolation?

813
00:53:17,249 --> 00:53:18,295
Power politics, eh?

814
00:53:18,406 --> 00:53:20,531
I have merely explained the position.
I cannot do more.

815
00:53:20,641 --> 00:53:22,647
I do hope that moderation will prevail.

816
00:53:22,756 --> 00:53:24,837
Moderation? He's an optimist.

817
00:53:24,951 --> 00:53:27,709
You're barmy, the lot of you.
We've had a good run and this is it.

818
00:53:27,825 --> 00:53:30,222
That's OK, Jim. If you want to turn
it in, nobody is going to stop you.

819
00:53:30,339 --> 00:53:31,795
But we're not going to stand for that.

820
00:53:31,855 --> 00:53:34,133
You can't push English people around
like sacks of potatoes.

821
00:53:34,249 --> 00:53:35,536
English?

822
00:53:35,646 --> 00:53:37,141
Don't you come that stuff, Jim Garland.

823
00:53:37,163 --> 00:53:39,680
We always were English
and we always will be English.

824
00:53:39,797 --> 00:53:41,039
And it's just because we are English

825
00:53:41,153 --> 00:53:43,595
that we're sticking out
for our right to be Burgundians.

826
00:53:43,708 --> 00:53:46,072
Hear, hear!

827
00:53:48,097 --> 00:53:50,418
- Good night.
- Good night.

828
00:53:57,715 --> 00:53:59,437
Well, you've burned
your boats now all right.

829
00:53:59,551 --> 00:54:02,951
Ha-ha! I have?
You haven't done so bad yourself.

830
00:54:03,062 --> 00:54:04,784
Worried?

831
00:54:04,898 --> 00:54:07,895
No, never felt less worried in my life.

832
00:54:08,011 --> 00:54:10,376
That's right, we'll show 'em.

833
00:54:10,485 --> 00:54:12,882
Only, what?
That's what I want to know.

834
00:54:12,999 --> 00:54:14,961
Yeah, you're not the only one.

835
00:54:17,429 --> 00:54:20,111
'The closing of
the frontier at ten o'clock this morning

836
00:54:20,143 --> 00:54:23,260
'marks the deadline
for the 19 families of Burgundy.

837
00:54:23,376 --> 00:54:26,853
'They have the choice of accepting
the Government's evacuation offer

838
00:54:26,968 --> 00:54:28,885
'or of subjecting themselves
and their children

839
00:54:30,878 --> 00:54:33,636
'to the hardships
of what would be virtually a siege.'

840
00:54:33,752 --> 00:54:37,664
Come along, children.

841
00:54:51,550 --> 00:54:54,111
Good old Steve! Have a bash!

842
00:54:57,736 --> 00:54:59,098
Binny, tell your Auntie Flo
about your heat rash.

843
00:54:59,212 --> 00:55:01,654
Now, Charlie, you tell the driver
when you're going to be sick.

844
00:55:06,994 --> 00:55:10,155
'Attention, please. Attention, please.

845
00:55:10,267 --> 00:55:12,632
'Anyone who wishes to leave this area

846
00:55:12,741 --> 00:55:16,413
'has precisely two minutes
in which to do so.'

847
00:55:16,533 --> 00:55:19,170
Just a minute.
You need a passport to get in here.

848
00:55:19,286 --> 00:55:21,128
Oi. What's the big idea?

849
00:55:21,241 --> 00:55:24,086
I'm with you, mate.
I was born here. My mother just told me.

850
00:55:24,195 --> 00:55:26,636
Honest? Come on in, then.

851
00:55:26,748 --> 00:55:30,824
'The frontier
will be closed in precisely one minute.

852
00:55:30,939 --> 00:55:33,576
'This is your last chance.'

853
00:55:33,692 --> 00:55:34,815
'Save your breath, mate.

854
00:55:34,930 --> 00:55:37,207
'We've made up our minds
and we're stopping right where we are.'

855
00:55:38,641 --> 00:55:40,200
'I'll thank you not to interrupt me.'

856
00:55:40,317 --> 00:55:42,235
'I'll thank you
not to raise your voice to me, sir.'

857
00:55:42,353 --> 00:55:44,598
'If I can't raise my voice
in my own country...'

858
00:55:44,707 --> 00:55:48,619
'We're sick and tired of
your voice in this country. Now, shut up!'

859
00:55:48,738 --> 00:55:51,573
'I beg your pardon?'
 'I said shut up!'

860
00:55:51,651 --> 00:55:53,971
'Shut up yourself!'

861
00:56:14,000 --> 00:56:16,920
- I told 'em, didn't I?
- Here comes "The Fourth Programme".

862
00:56:17,032 --> 00:56:18,917
Give us a glass of water.

863
00:56:22,261 --> 00:56:24,778
Don't you know there's a siege on?

864
00:56:55,783 --> 00:56:57,941
Cor, look at that,
the siege of Burgundy.

865
00:56:58,058 --> 00:56:59,942
I'd like to see that.

866
00:57:00,053 --> 00:57:02,298
Look at them pictures.

867
00:57:04,123 --> 00:57:06,804
She took my last coppers.

868
00:57:06,917 --> 00:57:10,469
- They ought to have let us in free.
- Get in your seat.

869
00:57:18,729 --> 00:57:21,410
'This week's exclusive
camera report tells of growing tension

870
00:57:21,523 --> 00:57:24,476
'on both sides of Burgundy's
self-imposed iron curtain.

871
00:57:24,596 --> 00:57:26,438
'For the first time since World War ll,

872
00:57:26,552 --> 00:57:28,590
'Britain's party politics
have been forgotten.

873
00:57:28,707 --> 00:57:30,352
'The nation's leaders
have come together

874
00:57:30,462 --> 00:57:33,862
'to seek a solution
to this unprecedented crisis.

875
00:57:37,925 --> 00:57:41,522
'Burgundy has enlarged its own privy
council to grapple with affairs of state.

876
00:57:41,637 --> 00:57:43,195
'Presiding over it is the Duke,

877
00:57:43,313 --> 00:57:46,713
'who has decided to remain with his
people in their national emergency.

878
00:57:46,824 --> 00:57:50,976
'At last, after 500 years, Burgundy
has avenged her ancient defeat

879
00:57:51,095 --> 00:57:52,457
'in the bloodless battle
of the underground,

880
00:57:52,571 --> 00:57:55,491
'has stepped once more
into the pages of the history book.

881
00:57:55,604 --> 00:57:58,404
'And today this newest brother
of the world democracies

882
00:57:58,518 --> 00:58:00,915
'is hammering out its internal policy.

883
00:58:01,032 --> 00:58:03,396
'Under the inspiration
of its ancient leader,

884
00:58:03,506 --> 00:58:05,783
'Burgundy adopts to the new way of life.

885
00:58:11,088 --> 00:58:12,091
'Rationing is severe,

886
00:58:12,205 --> 00:58:15,845
'and food from every home in Burgundy is
stored in the cellars of the state pub.

887
00:58:15,957 --> 00:58:17,799
'Food Minister is Miss Molly Reid.

888
00:58:17,913 --> 00:58:21,432
'Owing to shortage at the fish shop,
she became a displaced person.

889
00:58:21,544 --> 00:58:25,456
'Perhaps you will tell us something
about the Ministry, Miss Reid.'

890
00:58:25,575 --> 00:58:27,220
Well, it's ever so nice, really.

891
00:58:27,330 --> 00:58:28,530
I expect you feel very proud

892
00:58:28,647 --> 00:58:31,292
at having been directed to be guardian
angel over the national larder?

893
00:58:31,361 --> 00:58:34,521
Oh, yes, ever so.

894
00:58:34,634 --> 00:58:36,431
Do you want me to say anything else?

895
00:58:36,549 --> 00:58:39,469
'Many other changes
have taken place inside Burgundy,

896
00:58:39,582 --> 00:58:42,143
'not only in appearance
but also in the mode of living.

897
00:58:42,256 --> 00:58:45,656
'Now that all food is stored in once place
and meal times can be standardised,

898
00:58:45,768 --> 00:58:50,998
'communal feeding has been introduced under
the supervision of the Duke himself.

899
00:58:51,115 --> 00:58:52,880
'It is a great success.

900
00:58:52,991 --> 00:58:56,347
'Continental cooking
has so much more flavour.

901
00:58:59,376 --> 00:59:01,577
'Commercial dealings
have come to a standstill.

902
00:59:01,691 --> 00:59:04,535
'Behind locked doors, Burgundy's
Chancellor of the Exchequer

903
00:59:04,644 --> 00:59:07,128
'is trying to solve his country's
unique currency problem

904
00:59:07,238 --> 00:59:10,039
'of too much gold chasing
too few opportunities.

905
00:59:10,151 --> 00:59:12,908
'Would you care to say
a few words, sir?'

906
00:59:13,024 --> 00:59:16,261
Well, er... Pemberton and I have
made up our early differences

907
00:59:16,376 --> 00:59:17,695
and today in Burgundy

908
00:59:17,813 --> 00:59:22,411
we are absolutely unanimous
in our resolve to keep our treasure.

909
00:59:22,523 --> 00:59:24,561
'And now a word from
Burgundy's Prime Minister,

910
00:59:24,678 --> 00:59:26,203
'Mr Arthur Pemberton.'

911
00:59:26,313 --> 00:59:28,875
Er... yes, well, I'm happy to say that

912
00:59:28,988 --> 00:59:31,472
after early opposition
from the Pimlico Council,

913
00:59:31,581 --> 00:59:34,862
my long-cherished scheme
for an open-air swimming pool

914
00:59:34,974 --> 00:59:38,690
is now going ahead with the full
approval of the Burgundy Council.

915
00:59:38,805 --> 00:59:41,605
'And so the glory
of the resurrected State of Burgundy

916
00:59:41,718 --> 00:59:43,724
'rises like a phoenix from the ash cans.

917
00:59:43,833 --> 00:59:46,394
'But although this idea
was popular in the model stage,

918
00:59:46,507 --> 00:59:47,913
'the lunch whistle sounds a louder
message

919
00:59:48,023 --> 00:59:50,149
'than hitting the production target.

920
00:59:51,695 --> 00:59:53,853
'Like all other public
works in Burgundy,

921
00:59:53,969 --> 00:59:57,446
'this scheme is the result of a scientific
democratic analysis of public opinion.

922
01:00:06,540 --> 01:00:09,025
'The great drought caused
by London's longest heat wave

923
01:00:09,135 --> 01:00:13,014
'is the one serious threat
to Burgundy's independence.

924
01:00:13,125 --> 01:00:16,002
'80-year-old records for lack of
rainfall have all gone overboard.

925
01:00:16,118 --> 01:00:18,080
'Water is cut off, but liquor makes do.

926
01:00:18,194 --> 01:00:22,585
'So, Burgundy washes up in a pint of bitter,
and makes tea with a kettle of boiling gin.

927
01:00:22,703 --> 01:00:26,342
'In fact, Burgundians are spending
their water like money.

928
01:00:28,131 --> 01:00:30,332
'So, this strangest of all sieges
continues,

929
01:00:30,446 --> 01:00:33,726
'a matter of principle to the
Burgundians, a headache to Whitehall.

930
01:00:33,837 --> 01:00:36,158
'But wherever our sympathies may lie
in this cold war in the heat wave,

931
01:00:36,272 --> 01:00:38,876
'whatever the rights and wrongs
of the case,

932
01:00:38,985 --> 01:00:42,298
'one cannot but say,
"Plucky little Burgundy!"'

933
01:00:44,373 --> 01:00:45,975
Yippee! Yippee!

934
01:00:46,089 --> 01:00:48,606
That's my mum, that is, on the council!

935
01:00:51,476 --> 01:00:53,274
On the Council of Burgundy!

936
01:00:53,392 --> 01:00:56,792
Come here!
Come here, Monty! Come here!

937
01:01:17,696 --> 01:01:19,581
Hey!

938
01:01:27,233 --> 01:01:30,273
- Any news?
- I've no statement to make.

939
01:01:33,899 --> 01:01:36,263
There are exactly two gallons,
three quarts,

940
01:01:36,372 --> 01:01:40,251
and one and one eighth pints of water
left in the whole of Burgundy.

941
01:01:41,361 --> 01:01:44,041
Well, I move we pass
a law against washing.

942
01:01:44,154 --> 01:01:46,312
- What, in this kind of weather?
- Really?

943
01:01:46,429 --> 01:01:50,429
You keep quiet, my girl.
You're not even on this committee.

944
01:01:52,255 --> 01:01:54,697
Well, there it is.

945
01:01:54,810 --> 01:01:57,087
We must either get water, or else.

946
01:01:57,204 --> 01:02:02,043
Hey, we might make a sortie.
Like my ancestor at the siege of Dijon.

947
01:02:02,153 --> 01:02:04,354
The amount of water
we could carry back...

948
01:02:04,467 --> 01:02:06,265
Why don't you use your common sense?

949
01:02:06,383 --> 01:02:09,619
They've turned off the hydrant
at the corner, haven't they?

950
01:02:09,735 --> 01:02:11,936
Well, go and turn it on again.

951
01:02:15,881 --> 01:02:19,281
How many more weeks are we
going to walk round this barbed wire?

952
01:02:19,393 --> 01:02:20,712
Search me!

953
01:02:20,830 --> 01:02:24,262
What do they think this Burgundy mob's
gonna do'? Invade England?

954
01:02:24,381 --> 01:02:26,866
- Oh, good evening, officer.
- Good evening, sir.

955
01:02:26,975 --> 01:02:29,972
Oh, it's so hot, one cannot sleep.

956
01:02:30,088 --> 01:02:33,401
You know, it reminds me of a very,
very hot night on the Riviera,

957
01:02:33,520 --> 01:02:37,912
and there was a lovely brunette
and a beautiful blonde.

958
01:02:38,030 --> 01:02:39,991
I'd have laid an even monkey
there'd be moonlight.

959
01:02:40,105 --> 01:02:43,341
- Just our luck.
- Now, quiet as you can, everyone.

960
01:02:46,211 --> 01:02:49,688
But it must be terrible for you,
officer, wearing that thick uniform.

961
01:02:49,803 --> 01:02:50,838
Oh, that's all right, miss.

962
01:02:53,754 --> 01:02:55,792
Good luck, Ted.

963
01:03:14,864 --> 01:03:17,348
And lovely eyes.

964
01:03:36,335 --> 01:03:38,732
- What was that?
- I didn't hear anything.

965
01:03:38,849 --> 01:03:41,213
Must have been cats or something.
Do you like cats, officer?

966
01:04:03,791 --> 01:04:07,191
I don't care.
You're not going to do your pools now.

967
01:04:14,686 --> 01:04:17,966
- Where do you think you're going?
- You're drunk. Drunk in charge!

968
01:04:19,514 --> 01:04:22,631
Quite right, officer. I'll come quietly.

969
01:04:25,021 --> 01:04:28,781
No, I don't want to be too hard on you.
Be more careful in future.

970
01:05:09,958 --> 01:05:13,151
Hey! Hey! I say!

971
01:05:13,270 --> 01:05:15,428
Go on, beat it!

972
01:05:16,942 --> 01:05:18,784
Will you go away?

973
01:05:19,775 --> 01:05:22,292
- Why don't you arrest me?
- Oh, go on, go away!

974
01:05:22,409 --> 01:05:24,610
Well, why don't you arrest me?
This is a free country, isn't it?

975
01:05:24,724 --> 01:05:28,679
Hey! Will you go away?
Look, haven't you got a home?

976
01:05:30,550 --> 01:05:32,435
Blimey. Copper.

977
01:05:56,649 --> 01:05:59,134
I've had the police after me!

978
01:06:27,458 --> 01:06:29,659
Oh, it's good.

979
01:06:47,292 --> 01:06:48,818
Taken 'em longer than I expected.

980
01:06:48,928 --> 01:06:51,489
Look, they're taking no more chances.

981
01:06:51,602 --> 01:06:54,479
Jackson, to the right. Round up there.

982
01:06:54,595 --> 01:06:57,951
Who cares? Last us a month,
this little lot alone.

983
01:06:59,305 --> 01:07:01,582
- Mr Pemberton!
- Dad, come quick!

984
01:07:01,699 --> 01:07:03,617
- Would you come to the pub at once?
- What's up?

985
01:07:03,734 --> 01:07:06,371
Molly tried to wash her hands
when... when there was no water.

986
01:07:06,488 --> 01:07:09,212
- She left the tap turned on in the bar!
- Strewth!

987
01:07:30,672 --> 01:07:32,350
Well, it wasn't my fault.

988
01:07:32,468 --> 01:07:35,824
I didn't know you were gonna
turn the water on again.

989
01:07:35,940 --> 01:07:38,817
Nobody ever tells me anything!

990
01:07:38,933 --> 01:07:41,777
It's all right, Moll.
It's no use crying over spilt milk.

991
01:07:44,160 --> 01:07:45,958
Smith's Crisps!

992
01:07:47,792 --> 01:07:50,309
Four tins, that's all that's left.

993
01:07:50,426 --> 01:07:53,184
Everything else has had it.

994
01:07:53,300 --> 01:07:55,861
I reckon we've all had it this time.

995
01:08:06,269 --> 01:08:08,067
Well, we can't let them starve to death.

996
01:08:08,184 --> 01:08:10,908
We can't not let them starve to death.

997
01:08:11,018 --> 01:08:13,503
I wish we could pass it on to UNO.

998
01:08:16,047 --> 01:08:18,085
Well, why not?

999
01:08:19,359 --> 01:08:23,075
Maudie, can you get me a line
to Lake Success?

1000
01:08:23,190 --> 01:08:25,348
Yes, Success.

1001
01:08:29,815 --> 01:08:33,727
Hello?
Yes, sir? What, Burgundy?

1002
01:08:33,845 --> 01:08:35,927
Oh, Burgundy!

1003
01:08:36,040 --> 01:08:38,361
Really'? Yes, of course, sir.

1004
01:08:38,474 --> 01:08:41,591
We can have a coach standing by
for them. Yes, right you are, sir.

1005
01:08:41,707 --> 01:08:44,627
I say, they've had enough of it.
They're ready to pack it up.

1006
01:08:44,740 --> 01:08:46,102
- Statement in the press?
- Rather.

1007
01:08:46,217 --> 01:08:47,982
Fleet Street should do us proud on this.

1008
01:09:15,947 --> 01:09:17,953
Jolly rotten shame, that's what I say.

1009
01:09:18,063 --> 01:09:20,221
Yeah, starving people out.

1010
01:09:20,338 --> 01:09:24,054
Oi, come and have a look at this!

1011
01:09:56,933 --> 01:09:59,330
Five minutes to go.

1012
01:10:02,361 --> 01:10:05,161
- How do we go?
- By the same coach as the kids.

1013
01:10:05,273 --> 01:10:07,158
- Oh.
- That's that.

1014
01:10:10,222 --> 01:10:14,101
Now I know
what Napoleon felt like before Waterloo.

1015
01:10:14,213 --> 01:10:16,850
- After, Dad.
-  Mum!

1016
01:10:16,967 --> 01:10:18,492
- Hey, Dad!
-  Here you are, Mum.

1017
01:10:18,603 --> 01:10:20,880
- Dad!
- Here you are, Mum!

1018
01:10:28,939 --> 01:10:31,304
Give us another one,
there's a good boy.

1019
01:10:31,413 --> 01:10:34,649
Come on, Benny. Come on, my lad.

1020
01:10:34,765 --> 01:10:38,557
- Ah, what do you think of that?
- Been a good boy? Had a nice time?

1021
01:10:38,676 --> 01:10:42,076
Here you are, Mum, catch!
Here you are!

1022
01:10:42,188 --> 01:10:43,866
- I would have fetched more for you.
- Haven't got any more.

1023
01:10:43,984 --> 01:10:46,513
Pity I didn't have more money,
else I would have got you some more.

1024
01:10:46,618 --> 01:10:49,570
- I haven't got no more.
- I'm sorry I haven't got no more, Mum.

1025
01:10:49,690 --> 01:10:51,052
- No more?
- No, I haven't got no more money.

1026
01:10:51,167 --> 01:10:54,764
Mummy, here. Guess what'?
I saw you on a newsreel the other day.

1027
01:10:54,879 --> 01:10:57,156
You didn't half look good.

1028
01:11:05,134 --> 01:11:07,619
Oh, go on, Dad. Let me feed them too.

1029
01:11:07,729 --> 01:11:10,050
- Oh, go on. Go on, Dad, let me.
- All right, then, go on.

1030
01:11:10,163 --> 01:11:12,080
Here, that's our lunch!

1031
01:11:36,582 --> 01:11:37,901
<i>Ho“.!</i>

1032
01:11:48,594 --> 01:11:50,555
I'll ring the station.

1033
01:11:50,669 --> 01:11:53,470
Oranges! Nice sweet oranges!

1034
01:11:53,583 --> 01:11:54,586
Oranges!

1035
01:11:59,330 --> 01:12:01,694
Come on, give us a chance!

1036
01:12:02,801 --> 01:12:05,438
There they are, Pemberton.

1037
01:12:12,818 --> 01:12:14,496
- Who cares now?
- That's right.

1038
01:12:14,614 --> 01:12:17,098
Tell them what they can do
with their hearse.

1039
01:12:21,517 --> 01:12:23,763
- Mr Pemberton.
- Hello, Mr Straker.

1040
01:12:23,873 --> 01:12:25,638
- Your party ready?
- Well, I don't know.

1041
01:12:25,748 --> 01:12:28,145
Er... things have changed a bit,
haven't they?

1042
01:12:28,262 --> 01:12:29,744
Don't say our journey
is entirely fruitless.

1043
01:12:29,859 --> 01:12:31,813
Oh, I wouldn't say that.
We're always open to talk-.

1044
01:12:31,814 --> 01:12:34,059
But we expected this to be
unconditional surrender.

1045
01:12:34,169 --> 01:12:36,086
We... we have no powers to negotiate.

1046
01:12:36,204 --> 01:12:38,449
Well, sir, I suggest
you come back when you have.

1047
01:12:41,951 --> 01:12:45,863
- This is where we came in.
- Oh, I wouldn't worry.

1048
01:12:45,981 --> 01:12:48,782
This bit of food
won't last them more than a day.

1049
01:13:32,314 --> 01:13:35,267
I say no appeasement!

1050
01:13:49,235 --> 01:13:51,512
Britain can't buy gold.

1051
01:13:51,629 --> 01:13:53,035
Well, that's not
Burgundy's fault, is it?

1052
01:13:53,146 --> 01:13:54,824
Well, if you're not prepared
to meet us even halfway...

1053
01:13:54,941 --> 01:13:57,023
We are, buy half the gold.

1054
01:15:02,185 --> 01:15:04,909
Ah, my old beauty!
Up the Express Dairy!

1055
01:15:05,019 --> 01:15:06,306
Milko! Milko!

1056
01:15:06,416 --> 01:15:09,140
There she is, the old cow!
Right on time!

1057
01:15:09,249 --> 01:15:12,202
Bang on time! That's the old girl!

1058
01:15:12,322 --> 01:15:17,237
Come on, my little lady!
There's a sight for sore eyes!

1059
01:15:17,351 --> 01:15:19,312
OK?

1060
01:16:20,205 --> 01:16:23,245
Ladies and gentlemen,
I think I have the solution.

1061
01:16:23,357 --> 01:16:25,678
I propose that we lend
the capital of our treasure

1062
01:16:25,792 --> 01:16:27,133
to the Chancellor of the Exchequer,

1063
01:16:27,188 --> 01:16:30,501
while the interest is used for the
benefit of the Borough of Pimlico.

1064
01:16:30,621 --> 01:16:33,618
- A Burgundian loan to Britain.
- Ah.

1065
01:16:33,734 --> 01:16:35,815
My dear sir! My very dear sir!

1066
01:16:35,928 --> 01:16:38,129
A second Montagu Norman!

1067
01:16:54,925 --> 01:16:57,965
Careful, my man!
You will tear it.

1068
01:16:58,077 --> 01:17:00,954
This was the standard
presented to the Duke Charles

1069
01:17:01,070 --> 01:17:02,551
by the 14 burgers of Bruges.

1070
01:17:02,666 --> 01:17:07,821
I have assured the museum authorities
it shall be returned undamaged.

1071
01:17:12,963 --> 01:17:15,120
Real Burgundy!

1072
01:17:15,237 --> 01:17:18,877
You see this vineyard?
It's ten minutes from where we live.

1073
01:17:20,186 --> 01:17:22,583
When you come to Dijon,
I'll take you there.

1074
01:17:28,527 --> 01:17:32,678
Mr Huggins! It's sort of nice
being back at the old shop, isn't it?

1075
01:17:35,271 --> 01:17:37,592
- Is it?
- Yes.

1076
01:17:38,663 --> 01:17:41,027
I'd almost forgotten what it feels like,
handling a lobster.

1077
01:17:41,138 --> 01:17:43,099
Remember one day you said
you'd like to go to Billingsgate?

1078
01:17:43,212 --> 01:17:45,054
Yes?

1079
01:17:45,168 --> 01:17:47,533
Take you there tomorrow.

1080
01:17:47,642 --> 01:17:49,407
Oh, Mr Huggins.

1081
01:18:07,037 --> 01:18:09,957
I never thought anybody would be
pleased to see these things again.

1082
01:18:10,070 --> 01:18:13,264
You never know when you're well off
till you aren't.

1083
01:18:16,655 --> 01:18:18,976
Are you nearly ready?

1084
01:18:19,090 --> 01:18:21,531
Yes, shan't be long! Just about!

1085
01:18:25,714 --> 01:18:27,915
They're here!

1086
01:18:32,059 --> 01:18:34,816
Do you think we shall get
more than two main dishes?

1087
01:18:34,932 --> 01:18:39,324
I hope so. Haven't had a decent feed
since that last deadlock in Moscow.

1088
01:18:39,443 --> 01:18:42,995
And in these last few seconds
before your welcome return,

1089
01:18:43,114 --> 01:18:46,470
I am to express His Majesty's
Government's sincere appreciation

1090
01:18:46,586 --> 01:18:49,027
for your splendid conduct
of internal affairs

1091
01:18:49,140 --> 01:18:52,017
during your temporary absence
from the Kingdom.

1092
01:18:56,323 --> 01:18:57,926
Ladies and gentlemen!

1093
01:18:59,556 --> 01:19:01,398
We're back in England!
